the Department of Justice. It raises the ugly specter that the Department of Justice has been reduced to a political weapon for Trump. As Tribe said, there was “Not even a pretense of legality. They’re doing it because they can. It’s raw, naked, unprincipled, immoral power.”

Fortunately for us, there are courageous men and women in the Department of Justice who are willing to resign or withdraw in protest rather than participate in the perversion of the DOJ’s mission. On Tuesday, career prosecutors Adam C. Jed, Aaron Zelinsky, Michael J. Marando,
and Jonathan Kravis withdrew from the case against Roger Stone in protest over Barr’s political interference. Jonathan Kravis resigned from the Department of Justice. The DOJ then

filed a mealy-mouthed brief that said that the judge should do whatever she wanted regarding sentencing. With no one remaining from the original team to sign the brief, Acting Head of the Criminal Division,

John Crabb Jr., stepped in to stop the exodus of principled government servants who refused to cave to Trump’s political pressure. We have a new Robert Bork for our times. I don’t know John Crabb. He may be a swell guy. I do know that if he had refused to sign the revised brief

, the chain reaction of resistance to Trump may have continued until there was no one to sign the brief except Bill Barr. In stepping into the breach—even out of a misguided sense of duty—people like Mr. Crabb are enabling Trump’s politicization of the Department of Justice.

We need more people like Zelinsky, Jed, Marando, and Kravis—and fewer people like Crabb in the Department of Justice. That is what it will take to redeem the reputation of the DOJ. In a truly astounding, breathtaking turn of events, Trump then began a twitter attack on the judge

who will determine Stone’s sentence, Judge Amy Berman Jackson. Trump tweeted, Is this the Judge that put Paul Manafort in SOLITARY CONFINEMENT, something that not even mobster Al Capone had to endure? How did she treat Crooked Hillary Clinton? Just asking!

Not satisfied with Barr’s political intervention on behalf of Stone, Trump is now attempting to intimidate a federal judge presiding over a criminal trial. Chief Justice John Roberts should speak out to defend the federal judiciary! Republican Senators who gave Trump

a “get out of jail free” card should step in to protect the independence of the judiciary. They will not because they are in hiding, their heads hung in shame over their failure to stop the monster they have created. See The Hill, “Democrats call for Graham to launch Senate

probe into Roger Stone sentence recommendation.” (Blumenthal wrote to Graham, “This highly unusual about-face by the Department is stunning and alarming, and smacks of dangerous political interference in law enforcement decision-making.”) We must be realistic about the

threat posed by Bill Barr’s abandonment of independence and his willingness to act as Trump’s political errand boy. It is a serious threat to the rule of law. But we should take heart that some career professionals are willing to stand up to Trump—as Sally Yates did in January
2017. Mass resignations from the Department of Justice in solidarity with Zelinsky, Jed, Marando, and Kravis would hobble Barr and Trump. Will there be a chain reaction of resistance? Let’s hope so.
